@node welcome

	@{b}Welcome to the wonderful world of juggling!@{ub}

	A warning may be appropriate: Juggling can become an
	addiction! :)

	This little course consists of seven steps, and after
	following these steps, spending an hour or two of your
	invaluable time, you are actually juggling!

	When needed, pictures are included to clarify the text.
	(Ehh... Not allways, sorry!)

	If you learn the basic cascade, there are some tricks to
	deal with.

	@{b}Some things to think about before you begin:@{ub}

	*       Make sure you have three balls :) Tennis balls are ok
		but a little difficult for beginners because they will
		bounce out of your hands. Try finding some heavier
		balls to start with. Best of all, if you are just a
		little bit serious about juggling, buy real juggling
		balls. Beanbags are best for practise.

		You can make beanbags yourself. Maybe I'll include a
		description of that too, sometime... I haven't done
		any beanbags myself.

	*       Make room. You ARE going to drop. Put away that
		antique vase you got from from your grandma'... :)

	*       Make sure that nobody disturb you.

	*       Try to concentrate on the juggling!
	
	*       Have fun! (This is really important!)

	@{"  " link course}  GO for it!

@endnode

@node course

	@{b}THE 'THREE BALL CASCADE'
	************************@{ub}

	@{"  " link Step1.ilbm/main}  Step 1

	Hold one ball in either of your hands. Throw the ball in an
	arc from about waist height to your other hand. Say 'Throw'
	when you throw it and 'Catch' when you catch it. Easy! Now
	throw it back in the same way. You are now juggling one
	ball! :)
	
	Try this for about five minutes, until you think you can throw
	the same height and distance all the time. Only look slightly
	at the ball when it peaks.

	
	@{"  " link Step2.ilbm/main}  Step 2

	Now take two balls, one in each hand. Begin throwing with your
	weakest hand and throw to the other hand. When that ball
	peaks, throw the other ball in the same manner. Say 'throw,
	throw, catch, catch'. Practice 'til you can make ten throws
	without dropping.


	3.

	Same as step two but change the hand you start with.
	No need for a pic here...

	
	4.

	Take two balls in your best hand and one in the other.
	Repeat step two and three and let the third ball lie in your
	hand, watching the other two balls having fun :) Stick it
	between your thumb, third and fourth finger (the little finger
	and the one next to it). In other words, just forget about the
	third ball for the moment.

	
	@{"  " link Step5.ilbm/main}  Step 5

	NOTE: The dotted line represents
	the past, in this example the red ball has already been thrown
	and catched.

	This is the step when things starts to happen... Start as in
	step four, but when the second ball peaks, throw THE THIRD
	BALL! This is usually a little hard to do, but very soon you
	will get it. Just tell yourself that 'I WILL throw the ball
	this time!'

	Now, count 'one, two, three' instead of 'throw' and 'catch'.
	Count one time for each throw. Now learn this step and change
	the starting hand.


	6.

	As in step five, but when the THIRD ball peaks, throw the
	first ball back to its orignal hand. Count 'one, two, three,
	four'. You should now have two balls in your starting hand
	again.


	Now it's just a matter of getting it all together. Just keep
	throwing left, right, left, right and so on...

	@{b}You are now juggling!

	Beginner mistakes, tips etc :
	*****************************@{ub}

	The beginner will almost certainly walk forward while
	juggling. To straighten this out, stand in front af a wall.

	Try to throw the balls equally high.

	Always throw the balls @{b}under@{ub} the ball going down.

	Remember:

	* If you don't drop, you are probably not learning
	anything...

	* A touched ball is as good as if you had catched it because
	your hand knew where the ball was going...

	Practise, practise, practise!

	GOOD LUCK!


