@node tricks

	Some tricks to do:
	******************

	After learning a trick, try doing it while juggling, and then
	continue to juggle.

	@{"  " link trick1.ilbm/main} Throw above

	Instead of throwing one ball under the one falling down, throw
	it above. Called a 'reverse' throw.


	@{b}Throw under the arm@{ub}

	Just as you're going to throw, move your arm under the other
	and throw straight up. Then continue juggling. If you do this
	with the same ball all the time throwing with both right an
	left arm, you're juggling 'Tennis Upside-down', or something...

	
	@{"  " link trick2.ilbm/main} Rainbow cross

	Throw one ball high up in the middle. When that ball
	peaks, throw the other two so that they cross eachother. Catch
	the middle ball, and repeat. This is a 'columns' trick.


	@{"  " link trick3.ilbm/main} Two in one

	Learn to juggle two balls in one hand, in a circle, or paralell
	with eachother. There are three ways, 'columns', inside circles
	and outside circles. Look at the examples.


	@{"  " link trick4.ilbm/main} Columns

	Two balls in one hand goes up and down just like two
	elevators. Throw the third ball up and down in the other hand
	paralell to one of the other two balls. It's funniest when the
	two side balls are thrown in sync.


	@{"  " link trick5.ilbm/main} Jugglers' Tennis

	This trick looks very nice and you can start
	practising it after you have learned to throw 'reverse'
	throws.

	Take a ball that is different looking than the other two. Now,
	every time it's that balls turn, throw it *over* the other
	balls. This will make that ball going in it's own arc over
	the 'net' built up by the other two balls.


	@{b}'Fake' columns.@{ub}

	Juggle two in one hand. LIFT the
	left ball parallel with one of the other two balls.
	This looks quite funny.


	@{b}The 'Yo-Yo'.@{ub}

	Juggle two in one hand. Hold the third ball about
	15cm ABOVE one of the other two balls. This should look as if
	that ball hangs in a string under the third ball.


	@{b}Flashy three-ball-starts.@{ub}

	Hold all three balls in one hand in the
	shape of a triangle with the top of the triangle pointing
	forward. Throw all balls up in the air. Now one ball should
	go higher than the other two. Claw the other two balls and
	you are in the position of starting the usual three ball
	cascade.

	You can also point the top of the triangle towards yourself.
	Then, the lonely ball will go lower than the other two, so you
	can claw down on that one and than throw it straight up
	through the other two, grab them and start juggling.
	
	As you probably understand, the key to these two moves is to
	be quick. They are not difficult moves.



