@node shower

	The shower is the pattern that's usually in cartoons etc.
	The balls seems to go in a circle around the jugglers body.
	You start by holding two balls in your right hand. Throw both
	balls in rapid succession towards the other hand. Throw
	the second ball before the first one peaks. Practise this
	until you build up good speed.
	
	Next take one ball in your left hand and two in left.
	Now do the same exercise as before but when you have thrown
	the second ball from the right and are just to catch ball
	number one, throw the left ball in a straight line to the
	right hand (called a 'feed').

	Now it's just a matter of getting more and more
	throws all the time. This is usually where everything messes
	up. I have no tips but to practise, practise, practise. It IS
	a rather difficult and fast pattern.

	Try it for a couple of minutes every time you practise
	juggling and it will eventually come to you.

	Also try to practise from left to right instead. You'll
	probably be very dissapointed when that hand is even worse...

	If you want, you can try the two-ball-shower to start with.
	Take one ball in each hand and throw with the right and feed
	with the left hand. Try both ways.

	Happy showering!

@endnode

@node barrage

	Ok, here's a nice one. Burke's Barrage is one of the three
	(are there more) pattern with cooool names ;-) The other two
	are Mill's Mess and Rubensteins Revenge. You will NOT find RR
	in this guide until I can juggle it myself...

	Why don't we start now? Ok!

	Ball numbers in order of appearance...

	Take one ball in each hand. Cross left arm over right.
	Now you are going to do two things at the same time (pretty
	tough...).

	Throw the ball in your right hand straight up...
	...at the same time, carry the other ball in an arc over
	the rising ball. Continue to circle your lefgt arm around the
	right until you end up as in the beginning but now instead
	the right arm is over the left.

	Practise this on both sides.

	Now it's time to add the third ball. Take two balls
	in your right and one ball in your left hand.
	
	Do the same move as above, but when you have carried the ball
	about 180 degrees from where you started, throw ball number
	three and then catch ball number one.

	By the time you have catched ball number one, your carrying
	arm should be where it started, but crossed under your right
	arm instead of over.

	Now throw ball number one to the right of the pattern.

	Practise theese moves and throws on both sides and then try to
	mix it all together.

	When you have the pattern working, two balls should go up and
	down in the middle of the pattern, while the third should be
	carried around the other two. If you have different coloured
	balls, you will notice that one ball is always the same in the
	middle, while the other two are beeing carried back and forth.

	If it helps it's nice to know that the first ball you throw
	it's the ball being carried next time, i.e the ball that you
	first throw with your right hand straight up will be cathed by
	the right hand again, and then, when your arms are crossed
	again, your right hand will carry the first thrown ball around
	just as the left hand did in the first 'cycle'.

	(The previous sentence is probably a liiiittle bit too
	long...)

	The ball you first throw from your right hand will land in the
	right hand again just as you throw the ball that was being
	carried by the left hand.

	I'll try to improve the explanation of this trick when I have
	a better one... You just have to cope with it. :)

	At least I understand what I'm talking about. ;-)

	Sorry, no pictures, it would take up too much space to include
	in this guide....

	...and I'm too lazy to draw them...

@endnode

