@node box

	@{b}The Box@{ub} is a funny looking pattern that belongs to the family
	of square juggling. In square juggling the balls dont go in
	circles, they go in straight lines.

	This pattern is a difficult one. I think it's harder than
	Mill's Mess and Burke's Barrage, but that's me...

	Ok, how does the pattern look like?
	Imagine three balls (hard eh?...), one of them is going up and
	down in the left hand, one is going up and down in the right
	hand but not at the same time. As the right ball goes up, the
	left ball is falling down. AT THE SAME TIME as theese balls
	pop up and down, the third ball pops between the hands.

	It looks like this:

        .       ^
        :       |
        |       O
        O       :
	v ---O> .

	How to you learn it then?

	Take one ball in each hand.

	Throw the left hand ball straight up, and AT THE SAME TIME,
	throw the right hand ball straight into the left hand. Before
	the left hand ball falls down again, you must throw back the
	ball you last threw.

	This is a very confusing move and *I* don't know any easy ways
	to learn it.

	Oh well... Practise this on both sides.

	When you want to do the hole pattern, take two balls in your
	right hand and one in the left.

	Start by throwing a ball from your right hand, just to start
	the pattern.

	Now, just do as you did in the previous exercise, throw the
	left ball up and at the same time throw the second right ball
	to the left. I think you understand now and hope you have more
	luck than me doing it.

@endnode

@node mess

	Two gentlemen sitting at a bar. (If you like Monthy Pyton,
	you'll know what I mean...)
	
	"Your wife, can she... juggle?"

	"Urrrmm, yes, a little... Why?"

	"What tricks can she do?"

	"Three ball cascade, the shower, Mill's Mess..."

	"MILL'S MESS! SAY NO MORE!, SAY NO MORE!!"

	Probably the most famous pattern, and nice looking too :)


	Ok, why don't we skip the bullshit and jump straight to the
	pattern...

	Put ONE ball in your right hand and cross your right arm OVER
	the left.

	Throw the ball to the RIGHT, uncross your hands, catch the
	ball with your LEFT hand ON IT'S WAY DOWN, somewhere between
	the peak and the bottom of it's path.
	Do it on both sides, staring with the left hand over the
	right.

	That wasn't THAT hard, was it? No? I didn't think so...

	Take one ball in each hand, right arm crossed over left. Throw
	the right hand ball as before, uncross, but before you catch
	the ball with your left, you will have to throw the left hand
	ball to the right.

	Got it? Practise this on both sides until it feels smooth and
	easy.

	On to three balls, one in your left, two in your right hand.
	Do the first two throws from the previous exercise, and before
	you catch the secont ball, throw your third ball straight up
	to the left (your right arm will be crossed UNDER your left.

	Practise on both sides.

	Ok, what do we got here? Almost Mill's Mess, you just have to
	weld it together and this is probably the hardest to describe,
	therefore I don't. :)

	Ok, you'll get a little help.

	If you look at the third ball you throw, the one going
	straight up, you'll see (if you manage to freeze the picture
	somehow :), that all looks just like when you have threwn the
	very first ball, and you now have to do the same things as you
	had to do if it had been so...

	A little clarification...

	If you started with the right hand, the ball we talked about
	(the one going straight up you know) is the same ball you
	would have threwn, had you started with the left hand.

	I can't describe it better in words. I'll try to draw some
	pictures to include in future versins of this guide, though I
	don't think it will help THAT much...

	
	Maybe I don't take this patten serious now that I can do it
	myself, but it really isn't that difficult to do (for a couple
	of throws). I have said it before and I'll say it again:
	PRACTISE, PRACTISE, PRACTISE...

	Just be sure to mess it up and it will work out allright...

@endnode

